<subSubSection lastPageId="64" lastPageNumber="65" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="63.[140,1108,1434,1672]" lastBlockId="64.[140,1107,167,228]" lastPageId="64" lastPageNumber="65" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
Small (
<quantity box="[218,345,1469,1496]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="13.5" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="12.0">12–15 mm</quantity>
wingspan) moths with narrow lanceolate wings, usually with a conspicuous fringe on the tornal area of the forewing. This family is separated from similar yponomeutoid groups by details of the genitalia and venation. Larvae are leaftiers and skeletonizers or stem, bulb, and seed borers of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Jussieu" authorityYear="1789" box="[656,753,1575,1601]" class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Liliaceae</taxonomicName>
and a number of dicot families. Approximately 95 species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Heinemann" authorityYear="1870" box="[505,646,1610,1636]" class="Insecta" family="Acrolepiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Acrolepiidae</taxonomicName>
are known globally, most in the Palaearctic. Eight species are known in North America; one is known in AB. 
<bibRefCitation author="Gaedike R" box="[928,1107,1645,1671]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" pagination="179 - 194" refId="ref246140" refString="Gaedike R (1984) Revision der nearktischen und neotropischen Acrolepiidae (Lepidoptera) [Revision of the Nearctic and Neotropical Acrolepiidae (Lepidoptera)]. Entomologische Abhandlungen 47: 179 - 194." type="journal article" year="1984">Gaedike (1984)</bibRefCitation>
revised the family for North and South America. 
<bibRefCitation author="Landry J-F" box="[708,876,167,193]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" pagination="319 - 353" refId="ref254208" refString="Landry J-F (2007) Taxonomic review of the leek moth genus Acrolepiopsis (Lepidoptera: Acrolepiidae) in North America. Th e Canadian Entomologist 139: 319 - 353." type="journal article" year="2007">Landry (2007)</bibRefCitation>
reviewed the North American species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gaedike" authorityYear="1970" box="[370,506,202,228]" class="Insecta" family="Glyphipterigidae" genus="Acrolepiopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[370,506,202,228]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Acrolepiopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
